Question 1

  1. Simulate a series of =500 Gaussian white noise observations as in Example 1.7 of textbook and compute the smaple ACF, () to lag 20. Compare the sample ACF you obtained to the actual ACF, ().
  2. Repeat part (a) using only =50. How does changing n affect the results?

autocovariance = {sigma^2 if h=0 and 0 if h != 0} From example 2.17

library(astsa)
# a
#simulate a series gaussian n=500
layout(matrix(1:2,2), widths = c(2.5,1))
w = rnorm(500,0,1)
tsplot(w, col = 4, main = "White noise process with sample 500")
#compute ACF to lag 20
acf(w,20)

# b
#simulate a series gaussian n=500
layout(matrix(1:2,2), widths = c(2.5,1))
w2 = rnorm(50,0,1)
tsplot(w2, col = 4, main = "White noise process with sample 50")
#compute ACF to lag 20
acf(w2,20)

From the information stated avobe we know that the actual value of this series population ACF equals 1 at h=0 and 0 at any other value of h. From the plots we observe that the sample ACF fluctuates around zero after h=1. The amount of fluctuation increases with n=50. Thus increasing n from 50 to 500 decreases the ACF for non-zero values of h. AS n increases the sample ACF gets closer to the actual ACF.

Question 2.

  1. Simulate a series of n=500 moving average observations as in Example 1.8 of textbook and compute the sample ACF, (), to lag 20. Compare the sample ACF you obtained to the actual ACF, ().

  2. Repeat part (a) using only n=50. How does changing n affect the results.

autocovariance = {(3/9) sigma^2 for h=0, (2/9)sigma^2 for |h|=1, (1/9)sigma^2) for |h|=2, 0 for |h|>2} from example 2.18

and the ACF = {1 for h=0, (2/3) for |h|=1, (1/3) for |h|=2, 0 for |h|>2} from example 2.18

# a
#simulate a moving average n=500
layout(matrix(1:2,2), widths = c(2.5,1))
v = filter(w, sides = 2, filter = rep(1/3, 3))
tsplot(v, ylim = c(-3,3), col = 4, main = "Moving average with n=500")
#compute ACF to lag 20
v = v[!is.na(v)]
acf(v, 20)

# b
#simulate a moving average n=50
layout(matrix(1:2,2), widths = c(2.5,1))
v2 = filter(w2, sides = 2, filter = rep(1/3, 3))
tsplot(v2, ylim = c(-3,3), col = 4, main = "Moving average with n=50")
#compute ACF to lag 20
v2 = v2[!is.na(v2)]
acf(v2, 20)

If we compare the actual ACF to the ACF obtained from the series with sample size 500, we can see that the estimates for h=0,1,2 are very close to the actual values. However if we decrease the sample size to 50 only the ACF value for h=1 resembles the actual value. The ACF for |h|>1 is significantly less accurate.

  1. Fit the regression model
#jj is a collection of 84 numbers called a time series
plot(jj, ylab="Earnings per Share", main="J & J")

Q = factor(cycle(jj)) #make quarter factors
trend = time(jj) - 1970 #not necessary to center time -looks nicer
reg = lm(log(jj) ~  0 + trend + Q, na.action = NULL) #

  1. If the model is correct, what is the estimated average annual increase in the logged earnings per share?

The estimated average annual increase in the logged earnings per share can be taken from the summary table above. It is the addition of the estimates for Q (the seasonal component) namely 1.052793 + 1.080916 + 1.151024 + 0.882266 = 4.166999.

  1. If the model is correct, does the average logged earnings rate increase or decrease from the third quarter to the fourth quarter? And, by what percentage does it increase or decrease?

The rate decreases by 1.151024 - 0.882266 = 0.2687574. It decreased by (0.2687574/1.151024)x100 = 23.34941756 %.

When we include the intercept as done in the summary table above, the intercept takes on the weight of the first quarter, making the first quarter desapear, and affects all other seasonal terms by the amount of the first quarter. Thus this is a problem because we want to study each seasonal term separately.

After looking at the residuals ploted against time, their ACF and the superimposed chart, it seems that the model fits the data well so we can say that they do not look white.

Question 6

The glacial varve record plotted in Figure 3.9 exhibits some nonstationarity that can be improved by transforming to logarithms and some additional nonstationarity that can be corrected by differencing the logarithms.

  1. Argue that the glacial varves series, say , exhibits heteroscedasticity by computing the sample variance over the first half and the second half of the data. Argue that the transformation =() stabilizes the variance over the series. Plot the histograms of and to see whether the approximation to normality is improved by transforming the data.
varve_firsthalf = varve[1:317]
varve_secondhalf = varve[318:634]
#compute sample variance on the first half of the data 
var(varve_firsthalf)
## [1] 133.4574
#compute sample variance on the second half of the data
var(varve_secondhalf)
## [1] 594.4904
logvarve_firsthalf = log(varve[1:317])
logvarve_secondhalf = log(varve[318:634])
#compute sample variance on the first half of the data 
var(logvarve_firsthalf)
## [1] 0.2707217
#compute sample variance on the second half of the data
var(logvarve_secondhalf)
## [1] 0.451371

The glacial varves series shows heteroscedasticity in the comparison of the variance on the first half of the data and the second half of the data. These two variances are significantly different with the variance of the first half at 133.4574 and the variance of the second half at 594.4904.
Fortunatly the log transformation on X_t stabalizes the variance over the series. If we now compute the variance of the first half of the data and compare it to the variance of the second half of the data we obtain 0.2707217 against 0.451371 in the second half which is considerably more stable than the variance in the original data.

layout(matrix(1:4,2), widths = c(2.5,1))
par(mgp = c(1.6,0.6,0), mar = c(2,2,0.5,0)+0.5)
tsplot(varve, main = "", ylab = "",col = 4, margin = 0)
mtext("varve", side = 3, line = 0.5, cex = 1.2, font = 2, adj = 0)
tsplot(log(varve), main = "", ylab = "", col = 4, margin = 0)
mtext("log(varve)", side = 3, line = 0.5, cex = 1.2, font = 2, adj = 9)

qqnorm(varve, main = "", col = 4); qqline(varve, col = 2, lwd = 2)
qqnorm(log(varve), main = "", col = 4); qqline(log(varve), col = 2, lwd = 2)

with the help of these plots we can confirm that the approximation to normality is improved by transforming the data.

  1. Compute the difference =1, examine its time plot and sample ACF, and argue that differencing the logged varve data produces a reasonably stationary series.
layout(matrix(1:6,3), widths = c(2.5,1))
par(mgp = c(1.6,0.6,0), mar = c(2,2,0.5,0)+0.5)
tsplot(varve, main = "", ylab = "",col = 4, margin = 0)
mtext("varve", side = 3, line = 0.5, cex = 1.2, font = 2, adj = 0)
tsplot(log(varve), main = "", ylab = "", col = 4, margin = 0)

qqnorm(varve, main = "", col = 4); qqline(varve, col = 2, lwd = 2)
qqnorm(log(varve), main = "", col = 4); qqline(log(varve), col = 2, lwd = 2)
qqnorm(diff(log(varve)), main = "", col = 4); qqline(diff(log(varve)), col = 2, lwd = 2)

acf(diff(log(varve)))

The third plot contains the difference of the log of the varves data. It can already bee seen a more uniform behavior throughout in the time series plot as well as in the qq plot. In addition the ACF for the difference is shown above and it shows that the difference produces a reasonably stationary series.
